<exercises xml:id="ex-ByParts">
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Explain how we build the Integration by Parts formula, as well as what the purpose of this integration strategy is.
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            How do you choose options for <m>u</m> and <m>dv</m>? What are some good strategies to think about?
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Let's say that you make a choice for <m>u</m> and <m>dv</m> and begin working through the Integration by Parts strategy. How can you tell if you've made a poor choice for your parts? Can you <em>always</em> tell?
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Integrate the following.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint 3x\sin(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint 5xe^x\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint x^2e^{-x}\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint x^2\ln(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint x^2\cos(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint x^3e^{-x}\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint x\sin(x)\cos(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint e^x\sin(x)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint \sin^{-1}(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint \tan^{-1}(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Evaluate the following definite integrals.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint_{x=1}^{x=e} x\ln(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint_{x=0}^{x=\pi/4} x\cos(2x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint_{x=0}^{x=\ln(5)} xe^{x}\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                In this problem, we'll consider the integral <m>\dint \sin^2(x)\;dx</m>. We'll integrate this in two different ways!
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    We know that:
                    <me>
                        \dint \sin^2(x)\;dx = \dint \sin(x)\sin(x)\;dx
                    </me>. 
                    Use the Integration by Parts strategy, and especially note that you can solve for the integral (<xref ref="subsec-SolvingForIntegral" text="title"/>).
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    We can use a trigonometric identity to rewrite the integral:
                    <me>
                        \sin^2(x) = \dfrac{1-\cos(2x)}{2}
                    </me>.
                    So we have:
                    <me>
                        \int \sin^2(x)\;dx = \int \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{2}\cos(2x)\;dx
                    </me>.
                    Use <m>u</m>-substitution.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Were your answers the same or different? Should they be the same? Why or why not? Are they connected somehow? 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    They might be different, but they should only be different by, at most, a constant.
                </p>
            </hint>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For these next problems, we'll use <m>x=u^2</m> and <m>dx = 2u\;du</m> to substitute into the integral as written. Then use Integration by Parts.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint \sin(\sqrt{x})\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\dint e^{\sqrt{x}}\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="ex-IntegralLog"/>, we found that
                <me>
                    \int \ln(x)\;dx = x\ln(x)-x+C
                </me>.
                Let's find this result again, but in a different way.                
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    We'll start with a <m>u</m>-substitution. Let <m>u=\ln(x)</m>. Solve for <m>x</m>, and find a substitution for <m>dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x \amp = e^u</mrow>
                        <mrow> dx\amp = e^u\;du </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Apply your substitution above. You should have an integral for which you can use integration by parts! Integrate.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \int \ln(x)\;dx \amp = \int ue^u \;du</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = ue^u-\int e^u \;du</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = ue^u - e^u+C</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = x\ln(x)-x+C</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
</exercises>